 paternal family settled early in the century; the milieu of shady businessmen in Amsterdam that recruited Vermeer's grandfather to counterfeit coins; the artists, military contractors, and Protestant burghers who frequented the inn of Vermeer's father in Delft's Great Market Square; and the quiet, distinguished "Papists Corner" in which Vermeer, after marrying into a high-born Catholic family, retired to practice his art, while retaining ties with wealthy Protestant patrons. The relationship of Vermeer to his principal patron is one of many original discoveries in the book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aPainterszNetherlandsvBiography. 7aART / Individual Artists / General.2bisacsh  aAbraham Bloemaert.  aAelbert Cuyp.  aAmbrosius Bosschaert.  aBalthasar van der Ast.  aBalthus.  aBequest.  aBerchem.  aBolnes.  aBrouwer.  aBurgomaster.  aCarel Fabritius.  aCharles Baudelaire.  aClaes.  aConsignment.  aCornelis.  aCounter-Reformation.  aCurator.  aDe Graeff.  aDe Vos.  aDelfshaven.  aDelftware.  aDordrecht.  aEgbert van der Poel.  aEmanuel de Witte.  aFaience.  aFamilie.  aFerdinand Bol.  aFideicommissum.  aForay.  aFrans Hals.  aFrans van Mieris the Elder.  aGerard de Lairesse.  aGerrit.  aGorinchem.  aGoris.  aGovert Flinck.  aGuilder.  aHendrick Fromantiou.  aHendrick van Buyten.  aHenricus.  aHermanus.  aHilversum.  aHis Family.  aHouse of correction.  aIJssel.  aIsaac Massa.  aJacob Jordaens.  aJacobo.  aJan Lievens.  aJan Reynst.  aJan Steen.  aJan Verkolje.  aJan van Goyen.  aJeroen.  aJohan de Witt.  aJohannes Vermeer.  aKarel van Mander.  aLawrence Gowing.  aLeandro Bassano.  aLeonaert Bramer.  aMaria Thins.  aMauritshuis.  aMichael Kitson.  aMr.  aNotary.  aPatronymic.  aPhil